QAN.AX 12m Price Target: A\\$13.00 Price: A\\$11.11 Upside: \(17.0\%\)

1H result - in line with consensus / slightly below GSe. Revenue was \(+0.7\% / - 0.4\%\) vs GSe/Visible Alpha (VA) Consensus Data. Group Capacity was in line with expectations while group unit revenues (RASK) were \(+1\%\) vs GSe. PBT of A\\$2,394m was - 2% vs GSe and \(+0.4\%\) vs VA consensus. The lower PBT vs our estimate was mainly driven by slightly higher ex-fuel opex ( \(\sim +2\%\) vs GSe). With a \(\) 250m\(dividend and\) \ \(150m\) special dividend announced, management confirmed their intention/ability to distribute capital to shareholders while renewing the fleet.

Entering FY26 with a supportive demand backdrop. A highlight of the result is the solid top- line / demand momentum that QAN is carrying into FY26. 1H26 Guided capacity \((+5\%)\) and unit revenue growth \((+3 - 5\%)\%\) for Group Domestic and \(+2 - 3\%\) for Group International) were both ahead of our prior expectations. Further, expectations for capacity growth acceleration in the 2H points to management confidence in the outlook across 12 months. Importantly, QAN stated that intake trends through July and August were consistent with unit revenue guidance provided.

JQ - a lead indicator for renewal. Admittedly the business benefited from robust demand and benign fuel, but a \(300+\) bps uplift in Jetstar Group EBIT margin (despite a \(24\%\) uplift in D&A) is indicative of the upside associated with new fleet (JQ is most progressed on renewaht QAN took delivery of 17 new aircraft in FY25 with 11 in JQ40% of JQ's narrowbody capacity now refreshed). The group is expected to take delivery of 20 aircraft in FY26 with Qaetas taking 14 and this accelerating in FY27.

QANTAS AIRWAYS (QAN.AX)Source: Goldman Sachs Global Investment Research

Qantas Airways is the flagship carrier of Australia and is the largest airline in Australia by capacity share, serving destinations domestically and internationally. As a key beneficiary of the re- opening of the world post- COVID, the airline's traffic capacity returned to \(100\%\) of pre- COVID levels in FY25, with the airline's earnings capacity (EPS) exceeding that of pre- COVID levels by \(\sim 92\%\) . We believe that QAN's earnings capacity has been sustainably improved relative to pre- COVID, which provides a solid foundation for QAN's next stage of growth, with recent FY25 result reflecting upside associated with initial deliveries from QAN's fleet renewal program. Despite this, QAN is trading at a discount vs regional and US peers and at lower PE vs pre- COVID. Downside risks include: Slower- than- expected traffic and capacity growth given the uncertainty around fleet delivery, structurally reduced travel demand post- put- up post- pandemic demand, irrational market pricing leading to lower- than- expected yields/RASK, higher- than- expected fuel prices (with lower- than- expected pass- through) and unfavourable FX, lower- than- expected cost- out (net of inflation).

The Goldman Sachs Factor Profile provides investment context for a stock by comparing key attributes to the market (i.e. our universe of rated stocks) and its sector peers. The four key attributes depicted are: Growth, Financial Returns, Multiple (e.g. valuation) and Integrated (a composite of Growth, Financial Returns and Multiple). Growth, Financial Returns and Multiple are calculated by using normalized ranks for specific metrics for each stock. The normalized ranks for the metrics are then averaged and converted into percentiles for the relevant attribute. The precise calculation of each metric may vary depending on the fiscal year, industry and region, but the standard approach is as follows:

Growth is based on a stock's forward- looking sales growth, EBITDA growth and EPS growth (for financial stocks, only EPS and sales growth), with a higher percentile indicating a higher growth company. Financial Returns is based on a stock's forward- looking ROE, ROCE and CROCI (for financial stocks, only ROE), with a higher percentile indicating a company with higher financial returns. Multiple is based on a stock's forward- looking P/E, P/B, price/dividend (P/D), EV/EBITDA, EV/FCF and EV/Debt Adjusted Cash Flow (DACF) (for financial stocks, only P/E, P/B and P/D), with a higher percentile indicating a stock trading at a higher multiple. The Integrated percentile is calculated as the average of the Growth percentile, Financial Returns percentile and (100% - Multiple percentile).

Financial Returns and Multiple use the Goldman Sachs analyst forecasts at the fiscal year- end at least three quarters in the future. Growth uses inputs for the fiscal year at least seven quarters in the future compared with the year at least three quarters in the future (on a per- share basis for all metrics).
For a more detailed description of how we calculate the GS Factor Profile, please contact your GS representative.

Across our global coverage, we examine stocks using an M&A framework, considering both qualitative factors and quantitative factors (which may vary across sectors and regions) to incorporate the potential that certain companies could be acquired. We then assign a M&A rank as a means of scoring companies under our rated coverage from 1 to 3, with 1 representing high (30%- 50%) probability of the company becoming an acquisition target, 2 representing medium (15%- 30%) probability and 3 representing low (0%- 15%) probability. For companies ranked 1 or 2, in line with our standard departmental guidelines we incorporate an M&A component into our target price. M&A rank of 3 is considered immaterial and therefore does not factor into our price target, and may or may not be discussed in research.
